[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] In these elections, the winners were elected in 1877 after March 4.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] The special election in Pennsylvania was held March 20, 1877.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Republican Senator Simon Cameron had been elected to the United States Senate by the Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, in 1867 and was re-elected in 1873.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Following the resignation of Simon Cameron, the Pennsylvania General Assembly convened on March 20, 1877, to elect a new Senator to fill the vacancy.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Former United States Secretary of War J.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Donald Cameron, Simon Cameron's son, was elected to complete his father's term, set to expire on March 4, 1879.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Since his initial election in 1870, the Democratic Party had taken control of the Texas Legislature, ensuring that a Democrat would replace him.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Incumbent governor Richard Coke defeated former Texas Supreme Court justice John Ireland on the third ballot.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Representative John Hancock and former governor Fletcher Stockdale also ran, but they dropped out after the second round of balloting.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Caperton died July 26, 1876, in his second year in office.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Fellow-Democrat Samuel Price was appointed August 26, 1876 to continue the term, pending a special election in which he was a candidate.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Price lost the election to Democratic congressman Frank Hereford January 26, 1877 on the fourth ballot.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Appointed incumbent Samuel Price and challengers Frank Hereford and Henry S.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Walker, three prominent state Democrats, fought for the party's nomination over seven ballots and three sessions, without much movement in any direction.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] On January 26, with the Democrats unable to make a nomination, legislative Republicans broke the deadlock by throwing their support to Hereford on the floor.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Hereford resigned from the House January 31, 1877, thereby qualifying for the Senate.
