[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] In New York, the election was held on January 21, 1879, by the New York State Legislature.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Republican Roscoe Conkling had been re-elected in January 1873 to this seat, and his term would expire on March 3, 1879.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] At the State election in November 1877, 19 Republicans and 13 Democrats were elected for a two-year term (1878–1879) in the State Senate.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] At the State election in November 1878, 97 Republicans, 28 Democrats and 3 Greenbackers were elected for the session of 1879 to the Assembly, and Republican Thomas Murphy was elected to fill the vacancy in the State Senate caused by the death of Democrat John Morrissey.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] The 102nd New York State Legislature met from January 7 to May 22, 1879, at Albany, New York.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] The caucus of Republican State legislators met on January 20, Temporary President of the State Senate William H.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Present were all Republican legislators except State Senator Louis S.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Goebel (6th D.) and Assemblyman James W.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] The caucus of the Democratic State legislators met also on January 20.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Ecclesine (8th D.) offered to adopt a prostest against the senatorial election proceedings, claiming that the senatorial and assembly districts were incorrectly apportioned and thus the State Legislature did not represent the wish of the people of the State.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] The protest was substituted by a resolution to appoint a committee which would elaborate an address on the apportionment at a later date.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Ecclesine then marched out, and the remaining legislators nominated Lieutenant Governor William Dorsheimer for the U.S.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] The two Greenback assemblymen John Banfield (Chemung Co.) and George E.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Williams (Oswego Co.) voted for 87-year-old Peter Cooper, a New York City inventor, industrialist and philanthropist who had run for U.S. president in 1876 on the Greenback ticket.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Roscoe Conkling was the choice of both the Assembly and the State Senate, and was declared elected.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Note: The votes were cast on January 21, but both Houses met in a joint session on January 22 to compare nominations, and declare the result.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] In Pennsylvania, the election was held January 20, 1879.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Donald Cameron was re-elected by the Pennsylvania General Assembly to the United States Senate.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Simon Cameron resigned from office, his son J.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Donald Cameron was elected by the General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, in 1877 to serve the remainder of the unexpired term, which was to expire on March 4, 1879.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] The Pennsylvania General Assembly convened on January 20, 1879, to elect a Senator to serve the term beginning on March 4, 1879.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] The **1880 United States House of Representatives elections** were held for the most part on November 2, 1880, with five states holding theirs early between June and October.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] They coincided with the 1880 presidential election which was won by James A.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Garfield, who was a member of the House at the time.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Elections were held for 293 seats of the United States House of Representatives, representing 38 states, to serve in the 47th United States Congress.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] This was the first time that every state held their regular House elections on or before Election Day.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Special elections were also held throughout the year.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Issues such as Civil War loyalties, tariffs, graft and corruption dominated the year's elections, though none became substantive as a national issue.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] The economy was growing stronger after emerging from a long Depression.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] It was in this political environment that Garfield's Republican Party gained 19 seats and regained control of the House from the Democratic Party.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] The Greenback Party, an emerging party of workers and farmers, also lost seats in these elections, after gaining more than a dozen two years earlier.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] In 1880, no states held their elections after Election Day for the first time (California was the last state to hold late elections, in 1878).
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Maine held elections for its five members on September 13, 1880.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] Ohio held elections for its twenty members on October 12, 1880.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] Oregon held its election early on June 7, 1880.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] Texas held elections for its six members on June 1, 1880.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] Vermont held elections for its three members on September 7, 1880.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] Wisconsin elected eight members of congress on Election Day, November 2, 1880.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The **2016 United States presidential election in Colorado** was held on Tuesday, November 8, 2016, as part of the 2016 United States presidential election in which all 50 states plus the District of Columbia participated.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Colorado has nine electoral votes in the Electoral College.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Clinton received 48.2% of the vote, carrying the state's nine electoral votes.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Trump received 43.3% of the vote, thus marking a Democratic margin of victory of 4.9%.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] At the same time, Trump flipped five counties in the state: Conejos, Chaffee, Huerfano, Las Animas, and Pueblo.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The last two had not supported a Republican presidential candidate since Richard Nixon's landslide in 1972.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Despite Clinton's victory, this is the sole election since Colorado's Democratic winning streak from 2008 forward that the Democratic candidate's percentage in the state was held to only a plurality, while winning the state by a less than (albeit very narrowly in this case) 5% margin.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Colorado was also the only state that voted for Clinton won by a single digit in 2016 that would later vote for both Joe Biden in 2020 and Kamala Harris in 2024 by double digits.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] From April 2–8, 2016, conventions were held in each of Colorado's seven congressional districts.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Cruz swept all seven, winning 21 delegates total.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] On April 9, 2016, the state convention was held to elect the 13 statewide delegates and the 3 RNC delegates.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Again, Cruz won all 13 statewide at-large delegates.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Cruz was also the only candidate to address the state convention.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] A proposal to forbid Colorado Republican delegates from voting for Donald Trump was written in March 2016 by Robert Zubrin.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The group "Colorado Republicans for Liberty" handed out fliers of Zubrin's resolution at the state's convention.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Irregularities on the ballot were discovered at the state's convention.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Delegate #379 (Jerome Parks, a Trump delegate) was replaced on the ballot with a duplicate of delegate #378 (a Ted Cruz delegate).
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The Colorado Republican Party's Twitter account posted the message "We did it #NeverTrump" after Cruz received all the bound delegates at the April convention.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The party claims somebody hacked its Twitter account, and the party claims to be investigating how the message was posted.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] In May 2015, the Colorado Senate defeated a bill to hold a 2016 presidential primary.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] State senators Kevin Grantham, Kent Lambert, Laura J.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Woods, and Jerry Sonnenberg voted to stop the bill.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Sonnenberg, Woods, Grantham, and Lambert are members of the Ted Cruz "Colorado Leadership Team" for Ted Cruz.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Congressman Ken Buck and Colorado Secretary of State Wayne Williams are also members of the Ted Cruz "Colorado Leadership Team".
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The conventions were selected through statewide caucuses, which were conducted at the precinct level on March 1.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] No voter preference poll was held due to a decision in August by the state party to cancel it.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Marco Rubio and Ben Carson had dropped out of the race by the time the conventions were held, though they were still running during the March 1 caucuses.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] On April 3, the Green Party of Colorado held a presidential nominating convention in Centennial, Colorado, for registered Green voters.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] On April 4, the Green Party of Colorado announced that Jill Stein had won the convention and received all 5 delegates.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Throughout the race, Clinton lead in almost every poll in margins varying between 1 and 11 points, with a few polls showing a tie or a Trump lead.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] One of the last polls showed a tie between Clinton and Trump, but the last poll showed Clinton leading Trump 50% to 45%, which was very accurate compared to the results.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The average of the last three polls showed Clinton leading Trump 44% to 41%.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Voter turnout for the 2016 United States presidential election in Colorado was 72.4%.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Clinton won four of seven congressional districts, including one that elected a Republican.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Historically, Colorado has been, following the Bryan-Wilson period, one of the most Republican states in the nation.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Before 2016, no Republican had won without Colorado since 1908.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] However, increasing urbanization in the Front Range Urban Corridor, along with the growth of minority populations (especially Hispanics) have chipped away from Republican dominance in the state: while President George W.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Bush won the state in the 2004 election, it was one of the few states where Republican performance fell (with Bush's margin being nearly halved with respect to 2000), presaging Barack Obama's two Colorado wins in 2008 and 2012.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Trump did improve upon previous Republican candidates in Southern Colorado, carrying three of the area's counties (Conejos County, Las Animas County and Huerfano County), a feat not accomplished by any Republican since George H.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] He also carried Pueblo County by a 0.49% margin, becoming the first Republican to carry it since 1972.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Southern Colorado, a blue-collar, working-class, industrial area, had once been the state's Democratic stronghold, but Democratic dominance of the region is starting to fade.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Trump also did well in the traditionally Republican Western Slope, where counties such as Mesa County (home to Grand Junction) went for Trump by a 2–1 margin and the Eastern Plains, where Republicans often carried counties by 80% or more.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Hillary Clinton exceeded Obama's performance in the City and County of Denver and Boulder County.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] While these had long been the Democrats' main base in Colorado, Republicans had typically managed at least a quarter of the vote in the former and at least 30% in the latter when Colorado was a Republican state.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] In contrast, Trump managed only 18.9% and 22.0% in the two jurisdictions, respectively.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Hillary Clinton did not improve on Obama's performance in Larimer County (home of Fort Collins), but she did win the county, which had voted Republican in every election from 1920 through 2004 save 1936, 1964, and 1992, and Trump posted the worst showing for a Republican in the county since 1992.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Similarly, even though Clinton did not improve on Obama's showing in the suburban Denver-area counties of Arapahoe and Jefferson, she nevertheless carried both, both of which had been Republican strongholds up through 2004.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Trump posted some of the worst results Republicans have had in decades in this region.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Trump only won 39% of the vote in Arapahoe County, which includes some of the largest Denver suburbs such as Aurora and Centennial; before Obama won this county in 2008, this county had not gone Democratic since 1964.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Trump won only one county in the metro area (Douglas County—home to suburbs such as Parker, Highlands Ranch and Castle Rock), but with only 54% of the vote—one of the poorest performances in the area's most Republican county in decades.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Only in Adams County, the one county in the area outside the city of Denver itself that had been a Democratic stronghold prior to 2008, did Trump manage to improve upon Romney, but even here he was barely above 40% of the vote.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Meanwhile, while Trump did win the one remaining large Republican stronghold in the state, El Paso County (home of Colorado Springs), he won with only 56% of the vote, performing worse in the county than McCain in 2008 or Dole in 1996.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The confluence of Clinton's strength in Denver, Boulder, and the Denver suburbs, and Trump's weakness in El Paso County, ultimately handed the state to Clinton.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] As of the 2024 election, this is the most recent election where Chaffee County and Garfield County voted Republican and the most recent election where Alamosa County voted Democratic.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] It is also the most recent election where Colorado was decided by single digits, as the state has trended strongly towards the Democratic Party since.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Additionally, the 2016 results marked Trump's best performance in the state; he would go on to win 41.9% and 43.1% of the vote in Colorado in 2020 and 2024, respectively.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] This made Colorado the only state in the nation in which Trump's 2016 run was the best statewide performance out of his three runs in terms of vote share.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Colorado and Virginia have voted for the same presidential candidate in every election since 1996.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] However, this is the last time where Colorado would vote to the right of Virginia.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] In downballot races, Mike Coffman was ultimately able to hold on to his seat in a Clinton-carried district around Arapahoe County.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Democrats made big gains in this area in the State House and Senate.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] However, Republicans were able to gain a seat in Adams County, ultimately holding on to the State Senate.
